ew:{btn:"Previous competition videos",tabs:{tab1:"The Second SynBio Challenges",tab2:"The First SynBio Challenges"}},home:{group_2:{title:"About Synbio Challenges",p1:'Synbio Challenges is an international contest on synthetic biology. It is aimed at college students and graduate students who are passionate about synthetic biology while bringing together leading experts from around the world. It provides a forum for exchange between young scientists and leading experts face-to-face. Valuing the concept of "build for knowledge and build for use", Synbio Challenges encourages young scientists to start from their curiosity and explore innovative application of synthetic biology in diverse fields.',p2:"",p3:""},group_3:{title:"About Synthetic Biology",p1:"Synthetic biology is an emerging cross-disciplinary field and exemplifies technological convergence in life sciences. ",p2:"It seeks not only to modify life existing in nature, but make new forms of life in order to understand the design principle of life and develop a new generation of engineering biological systems. It integrates concepts from engineering and life sciences with a wide variety of enabling technologies. It has been considered to be key to understanding life and disruptive technology that will change our future.",p3:"In the past 20 years, a large amount of knowledge has accumulated in systems biology and genomics, accompanied by burgeoning technologies of DNA sequencing and synthesis, gene editing, machine learning for processing big data, and bio-foundry platforms, all of which have greatly advanced synthetic biology. In consequence, genetic realization of toggle switches and oscillators in living cells, de novo synthesis of virus, bacterial and yeast genomes, and the expansion of genetic codons to including unnatural amino acid epitomize the success of the young field in deepening our understanding of life. Meanwhile, mRNA vaccines, synthetic meat, large-scale synthesis by fermentation of natural products such as precursors for artemisinin and opioids and bio-based chemical raw materials, to name a few, start to provide an inkling on the impact capable of synthetic biology. It will continue to make ever more important contributions to human health, food security, green production, energy security, environmental security and biological security."},group_4:{title:"合成生物学竞赛介绍",p1:"合成生物学竞赛关注合成生物学创新及应用，致力于打通中国合成生物学领域的产、学、研、创、投通道，汇聚合成生物领域相关的学生和研究人员，联结高校、企业、资本、政府、园区、媒体、数据库等上下游全链条参与方，真正形成中国合成生物学的创新落地生态闭环，让合成生物学领域的创新想法有落地支撑的同时以产业需求驱动源头创新。"},group_5:{title:"Timeline",p1:"(UTC+8,Beijing)",p2:"Regular",p3:"Bacterial Gladiator",p4:"Protein Design",pw:"Judges",sz:"Rules",rc:"AGENDA"},group_6:{zd:"Advised  by",zb:"Organized by",cb:"Co-hosted by",lh:"Co-initiated by",zzs:"Sponsor"}},account:{login:"Login",email:"Email",password:"Password",forgotPassword:"Forgot password",enterEmailAddress:"Enter Email Address",enterPassword:"Enter password",noAddress:"Don’t have an accoun?",joinUsNow:"Join Us now",getCode:"Get verification code",resend:"Resend",passwordRule:"6-12 Characters",enterCode:"Enter Code",confirmPassword:"Confirm Password",confirmPassword2:"6-12 Characters",register:"Register",alreadyHaveAnAccount:"Already have an account?",Login:"Login",verificationCode:"Verification Code",signUp:"Sign Up",agree:"By joining, you agree to the ",terms:"Terms",emailError:"Format incorrect",emailEmpty:"Cannot be empty",passwordError:"Error. Your password must be 6-12 characters, of which at least 1 must be numeric, 1 uppercase letter and 1 lowercase letter. Example : Abc123",passwordEmpty:"Cannot be empty",same:"The confirmation password is not identical. Please enter your passwords again.",codeError:"Wrong verification code",codeEmpty:"Cannot be empty",emailRegister:"Email",resetYourPassword:"Forgot Your Password?",resetYourPassword2:"Reset your password",backToLogin:"Back to Login",newPassword:"New Password"},footer:{consultation:"Competition consultation:",complaint:"Challenge or complaint:",competitionRules:"Competition rules",privacy:"Privacy"},application:{home:{title:"New ways of playing with synthetic biology like never before",p1:"SynBio Challenges consist of six parallel tracks of competitions: Regular, Bacterial Gladiator, Protein Design by AI, Synthetic Cells, and Responsible Innovation in Life Sciences, as well as the new track added in 2026—Industry Challenges.",p2:"In Regular track, teams are evaluated on their scientific caliber first in the video presentation of projects they pick on their own and conduct research on with guidance from their advisors. In the finale, each team is challenged to provide answer to a hard problem, which varies team from team and is made available to the teams only 1 day before their defense.",p3:"In the track of Bacterial Gladiator, teams engineer the chassis bacterial strains provided by the organizing committee, and mail them back to the committee. Head-to-head matches are conducted using Shenzhen Infrastructure of Synthetic Biology. The team whose strain occupies bigger territory in the arena wins.",p4:"In the track of Protein Design, teams use datasets provided by the organizing committee to train their AI models and predict protein mutants with enhanced molecular performance. Shenzhen Infrastructure of Synthetic Biology will then construct, express, and characterize these protein mutants, and the team that predicts the highest-activity mutant wins.",p5:"In the track of Synthetic Cells, teams design a DNA sequence of no more than 140 bp (including promoters, 5’UTRs, and RBSs) based on molecular biology principles of gene expression and databases from literature. The sequence is used to express a color protein in a txtl system based on E. coli lysate, and the team with the highest protein expression level wins.",p6:"Teams may choose to compete in one or more of the above tracks based on their interests.",p7:"In the Responsible Innovation in Life Sciences track, participating teams may select either cutting-edge research areas such as synthetic biology or specific segments of bioeconomic industrial innovation. By integrating technological advancements with social research, experimental studies, or field investigations, teams are required to analyze potential ethical and safety risks and propose technological or policy solutions that foster responsible innovation and enhance biosafety in these fields. Judges will conduct comprehensive evaluations of the submitted proposals, assessing the scientific rigor, innovativeness, feasibility, and interdisciplinary collaborative capabilities demonstrated by the teams in problem analysis and resolution.",p8:"In the Industry Challenges track, participants are not limited to students. Companies will release synthetic biology projects related to their actual production and operations, open to all interested teams. Both project proposals and outcomes—including preliminary experimental results or more mature achievements—are eligible for submission. Outstanding teams may receive corporate funding to advance their projects through collaboration.",cont:"Participated"},routine:{tabs:{tab1:"Rules",tab2:"Prizes"},rules:{group7:{title:"Competition grouping",p1:"Teams can choose one group to the direction of the project. At present, the group is divided into the following three categories:",p2:"White for industry",p3:"Green for Agriculture, Environment",p4:"Red for Health, Medical treatment"},group1:{title:"Team requirements",p1:"A team consists of undergraduate and optionally graduate students, no more than 15 in total. Each team needs a leader who must be an undergraduate student. Graduate students should not exceed 20%. Each team needs an advisor from the faculty of a university or research institute.",p2:"",p3:""},group2:{title:"Participation",subheadings1:"Materials needed:",p1:"1. A video clip of 8 min(no more than 300M in size) presents your synthetic biology project.Any formats and styles are welcome as long as the content conveys enough information for the judges to evaluate the quality of the project.",p2:"2. A poster (57cm wide× 84cm tall) to summarize your project",p3:"3. If team wants to participate in the question of the project.<br/>4. Others: ",btn1:"Integrity Declaration Form ",btn2:"Bioethics and Biosafety Consent Form ",btns:"Download Template",subheadings2:"How to submit: ",p4:"Before te deadline, register a team account and submit information which nees to upload."},group3:{title:"Stages of  the contest",subheadings1:"Preliminaries:",p1:"Video clips are evaluated by our judges according the rubric with full scores of 100. All clips will be made public on our website shortly after the registry closes.",p2:"",p3:"",p4:"",subheadings2:"Final:",p5:"",p6:"The judges will prepare one challenge question based on the team project for each team. All teams will have half a day to prepare for the question before answering it on stage, with 5 min presentation and 10 min further Q&A with the judges. The full scores are 100. A team’s final scores are composite: 40% final plus 60% preliminary.",p7:"",p8:"Afterwards, a panel discussion will be held where team members are encouraged to participate in discussion with other teams. This discussion is not scored and intended for exchange and brainstorming."},group4:{title:"Rubric",subheadings1:"",p1:"For both video clips from the preliminaries and presentions in the final. The judges will score a team’s performance on four dimensions. ",subheadings2:"",p2:"",p3:""},group5:{title:"Scoring Rubrics",p3:"Scientific",p4:"Is your question of scientific significance?",p1:"Creative",p2:"Is there anything new in your design, technique or conceptualization?",p5:"Logical",p6:"Is your project complete in structure and sound in logic?",p7:"Doable",p8:"Is your project pure imagination or based on firm ground?"},group6:{p1:"Synbio Challenges Award",p2:"White for Industry Award  ",p3:"Green for Agriculture, Environment Award",p4:"Red for Health, Medical Treatment Award",p5:"Gold Medals",p6:"Silver Medals",p7:"Popularity Award",p8:"Best Oral Defence",p9:"Best Popular Science Article Award"},group8:{title:"Polaris Toolkit Gene Design Tool:",p1:'The organizing committee recommends the one-stop automated gene circuit assembly tool Polaris Toolkit, officially developed by ShenzhenSynBio Foundry, Simply submit your design requirements, and the intelligent platform will automatically complete sequence optimization,part assembly and assembly verification. This significantly shortens the "design-build-test" cycle and helps participants rapidly implementtheir synthetic biology designs.',btn1:"Polaris Toolkit",btn2:"Tutorials",file1:"KitTutorial.zip"},btn:"Register"}},protein:{rules:{title:"Rules",p0:"<b>Objective:</b> Use computational methods to design GFP variants with both high fluorescence brightness and excellent thermal stability.",p1:"<b>Basis:</b> Start from the provided wild-type GFP sequence.",p2:"<b>Task:</b> The candidate sequence can be designed from scratch or optimized based on any reference sequence from the GFP family.",p3:"<b>Submission:</b> Teams need to submit 6 designed and predicted mutant sequences.",p4:"<b>Verification:</b> The synthetic biology large - scale facility will synthesize, express (CFPS), measure the initial brightness (Finitial), conduct heat treatment, and measure the post - heat brightness (Ffinal) for all sequences that pass the verification (correct format, not in the exclusion list). Each batch contains a WT control.",t1:"<b>Protein Information:</b>",p5:'Protein information required for the competition (GFP sequence, structure, related data, etc.) has been uploaded to the registration system. When filling in registration information, participants may click the "Download Materials" button in the material submission section to obtain all official documents in one click.',t2:"<b>Scoring Rules (for single Sequence):</b>",p6:"Relative Brightness Score =Finitial/FinitialWT (Evaluates folding efficiency and extinction coefficient in the Cell-Free system.)<br>Thermal Stability Retention Score =Ffinal/Finitial (Evaluates the ability to resist denaturation at 72°C.)<br>Extremely Low Brightness Elimination:If the initial brightness of a submitted sequence is less than 30% of the wild-type sfGFP in the same batch (i.e., Finitial<0.3×FinitialWT), the fundamental structure/function of the protein is considered severely disrupted. The sequence will be eliminated directly, and both its component scores and total score will be recorded as 0.<br>Comprehensive Dual-Performance Score per Sequence = Relative Brightness Score × Thermal Stability Retention Score =",t3:"<b>Award Rules:</b>",p7:"The highest-scoring sequence (Best Top 1) among the 6 submitted sequences by each team will be used as the team’s final ranking score.The top 30% of teams will receive Gold Awards, and a defined proportion of remaining teams will receive Silver Awards.In addition, separate honors will be awarded for the Best Brightness Award and Best Thermal Stability Award, determined by individual component scores.",p8:"Award 1: Best Brightness Award (Top 3): Ranked according to the team brightness total score. </br> Award 2: Best Thermal Stability Award (Top 3): Ranked according to the team thermal stability total score (if the scores are the same, the team with the higher brightness total score has priority). </br>Award 3: Gold/Silver Award (comprehensive ranking approximately in the top 30% - 50%).",t4:"<b>Submission materials:</b>",p9:"1. Sequence File (.csv)<br>&nbsp;(1) A maximum of 6 amino acid sequences may be submitted per team.<br>&nbsp;(2) Sequence length is strictly restricted to 220–250 amino acids.<br>&nbsp;(3) Character Norms: Sequences must start with methionine (M); only uppercase letters representing the 20 standard amino acids are allowed. Stop codons (*) and punctuation marks are strictly prohibited.<br>&nbsp;(4) The competition sequence may be designed from scratch or optimized based on any reference sequence of the GFP family, without requiring sfGFP as the parent sequence.<br>&nbsp;(5) The mega-facility will uniformly synthesize the DNA templates (already containing the promoter, RBS, and terminator, with standardized concentration), so you only need to provide the amino acid sequences.Reverse translation will be performed using the open-source DNA Chisel algorithm.<br>&nbsp;(6) Before submitting, please cross-check each sequence against the Exclusion_List.csv to ensure that none of your 6 submitted sequences appear in the provided exclusion list.<br>&nbsp;(7) Header Norms: The file must contain exactly three columns with the headers: Team_Name, Seq_ID (e.g., 1, 2, 3…), and Sequence (amino acid sequence). Please refer to submission_template.csv.<br>2. Design Concept and Documentation (.pdf)<br>&nbsp;(1) Showcase your complete pipeline for generating sequences, whether from scratch or by combining existing models (e.g., ESM, ProteinMPNN, etc.). Explain your algorithm pipeline, how you balanced the brightness and stability objectives, and the reasoning behind selecting these final 6 sequences.<br>&nbsp;(2) LLM Agent: The use of various Large Language Models and code Agents is encouraged and welcome. If an Agent was used for the design, you must display the Agent’s logic tree and key execution logs in the document to ensure the process is reproducible.<br>&nbsp;(3) This document will serve as a presentation and conceptual reference for the judging panel. In cases where objective scores are similar, teams with clear logic, cutting-edge technical pathways, and open-source practices will be prioritized for promotion and showcase.<br>3. Open-Source Project Link<br>&nbsp;(1) A public repository link (GitHub, GitLab, HuggingFace, etc.) must be submitted to ensure reproducibility.<br>&nbsp;(2) The root directory must contain a README.md that clearly explains the environment configuration requirements, model dependency libraries, and instructions on how to run the inference code.",btn:"Register",a1:"Project Info",a2:"6 predicted high-performance sequences",a3:"Excel or Csv document, less than 10Mb",a4:"Open-Source Project Link",a5:"Please write GitHub/GitLab/HuggingFace or other code hosting repository link in a txt document and upload it.",a6:"Algorithm design introduction",a7:"Word or PDF document, no more than 10M",downBtnName:"Download Data"},message:"Notice:  If there are any questions, please contact us through info{'@'}synbiochallenges.com"},bacteria:{title:"Rules",p0:"",p1:"",p2:"",p3:"",p4:"Incubate for 48 h\nprocess the data\nand score",p5:"",p6:"Chemotaxis Video of Red and Green Bacterial Strains",p7:"(Chinese mainland teams only)",p8:"Red wins",btn:"Register",message:""},synthetic_cell:{title:"Rules",t1:"<b>I. Background</b>",p1:"The assembly of artificial synthetic cells with characteristics such as metabolism, growth, replication, and division using organic macromolecules like proteins and nucleic acids is a latest frontier in synthetic biology. Its realization will not only redefine our understanding of life but also revolutionize the application domains of biotechnology. This track focuses on the core synthetic cell research: the design of genetic circuits and their expression in cell-free systems. Specifically, the sequences of promoters, RBS, 5' UTR, and their combinations influence the expression of target genes. For example, it is known that the secondary structure of the 5' UTR is critical for mRNA half-life, but quantitative and predictive model is lacking. How to design regulatory sequences to maximize the expression of target genes is still an unresolved problem.",t2:"<b>II. Team Requirements</b>",p2:"ach participating team should consist of no more than 15 members (advisors are not counted in the total).",t3:"<b>III. Submission Format</b>",p3:'<b style="color:#597AFB">Design a DNA sequence no longer than 140 bp </b>(as shown in the blue section of the figure below), including the promoter region for T7 RNA polymerase and the 5\' UTR (containing RBS), up to the start codon ATG (including ATG).',p4:"After the teams submit the above sequence, the Committee will synthesize them and use the Shenzhen Infrastructure for Synthetic Biology to assemble this regulatory sequence with upstream and downstream sequences via fusion PCR, resulting a single DNA fragment. The fragment will be quantified and added to a standardized cell-free system of E. coli lysate for a 6-hour reaction. The GFP expression level will be quantified by measuring the reaction color.",t4:"<b>IV. Scoring</b>",p5:"The GFP expression level in the cell-free system reaction measured as above will be taken as the team's score.",t5:"<b>V. Awards</b>",li1:"Best Track Award: 1 team",li2:"Gold Award: Teams ranked in the top 50% of scores",li3:"Silver Award: Teams ranked in the bottom 50% of scores",btn:"Register"},technological_innovation:{title:"Rules",t1:"<b>I.Competition Overview</b>",p1:"Biosecurity Competition: Participating teams may select a cutting-edge area in life sciences (e.g., synthetic biology) or a segment of the bioeconomy industry. By integrating both scientific advancements and societal perspectives through research, experimentation, or field studies, teams will analyze potential ethical, legal, social and safety &amp; security risks and propose scientific or policy solutions to foster responsible innovation and enhance biosecurity. Judges will evaluate submissions based on the scientific rigor, innovation, feasibility, and interdisciplinary collaboration demonstrated in addressing the challenges.",t2:"<b>II.Team Requirements</b>",p2:"1. Team members must be current undergraduate or graduate students.<br />2. Teams may include up to 7 members (excluding advisors).<br />3. Teams must be interdisciplinary, with members from both STEM and humanities/social sciences backgrounds.<br />4. Advisors are optional, and members may come from different institutions.",t3:"<b>III. Submission Format</b>",p3:"Teams must submit a report addressing their chosen issue. The report should include:",p4:"Current situations based on scientific experiments, surveys, or investigations, and analyze ethical, safety, security, and societal risks or opportunities",p5:"Propose solutions (technical, policy, or practical) to promote responsible innovation and biosecurity.",p6:"Teams are encouraged to explore freely according to their team strengths, and the final submission can be either pure policy recommendations, scientific and technological solutions (such as embedded biocontainment measures), or practical projects (such as biosecurity training and education).<br />The submission should be in English.",t4:"<b>IV. Competition Form</b>",p7:'<b>Preliminary Round:</b>Online evaluation of submitted reports.</br><b>Final Round:</b>On-site oral defense and Q&amp;A with judges. Final scores combine preliminary and final rounds performance, weighted by 50% and 50%, respectively.</br><b>Engagement Session:</b>A youth forum on "Responsible Innovation in Life Sciences" will be held during the finals, featuring discussions among experts and teams. Top finalists will present at the forum.',t5:"<b>V. Awards</b>",p8:"",li1:"Best of the track (1 team)",li2:"Gold and Silver Awards (multiple)",t6:"<b>VI. Suggested Topics</b>",p9:"Teams may explore self-defined issues in life sciences or the bioeconomy. Examples include but not limited to:",p10:"<b>1. Responsible Innovation in Cutting-Edge Life Sciences:</b>",li3:"AI-synthetic biology convergence",li4:"Synthetic cells",li5:"Mirror life systems",li6:"[...]",p11:"<b>2. Governance, Rules and Development Strategies:</b>",li7:"Intellectual property protection for Synbio-designed organisms",li8:"Policy mechanisms for resolving genetic resource access and benefit-sharing disputes under the Convention on Biological Diversity",li9:"Strategies to leverage Asia’s bioresources and promote regional collaboration in life sciences",li10:"[...]",p12:"<b>3. Strengthening Global and Regional Biosecurity Systems:</b>",li11:"Enhancing regional biosecurity cooperation post the 2024 Southeast Asia Biosecurity Workshop in Shenzhen",li12:"Reinforcing the Biological Weapons Convention (BWC) in light of emerging biotechnologies (2025 marks its 50th anniversary)",li13:"Designing youth education programs on biosecurity and biosecurity",li14:"[...]",btn:"Register"},industry_challenges:{rules:{title:"Rules",p0:"I.Track Overview",p1:"To help students intuit the real world of industry, SynBio Challenges partners with leading companies in biomanufacturing. The companies provide real-life challenges the industry faces for the students and any others who are interested to solve. Solutions either with conceptual framework only or already having preliminary experimental results are both eligible. Winning teams will have the opportunity to receive investment from the companies and work with them for implementation of the solutions.",p2:"II.Team Requirements",p3:"1. Eligible Participants: Undergraduate, master’s, and doctoral students enrolled in universities, or startup companies (please consult with us for eligibility by emial). Individuals or group of team members may participate.",p4:"III.Submission Materials",p5:"1. Project Proposal, covering but not limited to:<br/>&nbsp; • Team introduction;<br/>&nbsp; • Background for the challenge to be tackled;<br/>&nbsp; • Proposed solution and its rationale;<br/>&nbsp; • Technical pipelines, feasibility analysis, expected outcomes or preliminary data;<br/>&nbsp; • Intellectual property statement, references.",p6:"2. 8-minute project video",p7:"3. Project poster (in English)",p8:"4. Others:",btn1:"Integrity Commitment Letter",btn2:"Bioethics Commitment Letter (if applicable)",btns:"Download Template",p9:"IV.Competition Format",p10:"<b>1.\tPreliminary Round (Online Review)</b><br/>Submit all materials; judges review online, focusing on innovation, scientificity, feasibility, matching degree with challenges, and completeness. Full score: 100 points.<br/><b>2.\tFinal Round (On-site Defense)</b><br/>On-site Roadshow: Presentation and Q&A based on the project. Total presentation duration: 15 minutes. Full score: 100 points.<br/>Same scoring criteria as the preliminary round, with a high proportion of enterprise judges, focusing on implementation value, cost, and industrialization prospects. ",p11:"V.Scoring Rubrics",p12:"• \t<b>Innovation:</b> Degree of innovation in design and practice, intensity of technological breakthroughs;<br/>\t• \t<b>Scientificity:</b> Rigorous logic, solid data, compliance with synthetic biology principles;<br/>\t• \t<b>Feasibility:</b> Experimental operability, cost, cycle, and controllable risks;<br/>\t• \t<b>Enterprise Need Matching:</b> Accurate solution to proposition pain points and industrialization potential;<br/>\t• \t<b>Completeness:</b> Complete materials, clear expression, and defense performance.",p13:"VI.Awards and Benefits",p14:"• \t<b>Awards:</b> Enterprise Special Award, Gold/Silver Awards (several);<br>• \t<b>Benefits:</b> Corporate experts will attend the finals as judges. If the team’s project is recognized, it will have the opportunity to conduct in-depth resource connection and cooperation with leading industry enterprises, jointly promoting project incubation and product development.",p15:"VII. Enterprise Topics",p16:"The following topics are released by various enterprises for the 2026 SynBio Challenges – Industry Challenges Track:",p17:"1.Kweichow Moutai Co., Ltd.",p18:"<b>Topic 1: Engineering Construction and Performance Optimization of Chassis Cells for Brewing Microorganisms</b>",p18_1:"Background: Brewing microorganisms such as Saccharomyces pastorianus, Schizosaccharomyces pombe, Lactobacillus acetotolerans Jinshan, Lactobacillus plantarum, Paecilomyces, and Monascus are the core production carriers in the fermentation industry. Their performance directly determines fermentation efficiency, product quality, and production stability. Traditional brewing systems mostly rely on natural strains or complex microbial communities, which suffer from unstable components, uncontrollable metabolism, and large batch-to-batch variations, failing to meet the requirements of standardization and controllability in modern biomanufacturing. In recent years, the development of synthetic biology has provided a new approach for the rational design of chassis cells. Through gene editing, metabolic regulation, adaptive evolution, and other methods, targeted optimization of microbial performance can be achieved. However, current research mostly focuses on the preliminary construction of chassis cells, and systematic optimization for fermentation efficiency, environmental stress tolerance, and industrial adaptability remains insufficient. ",p18_2:"Constructing engineered brewing microbial chassis cells with high conversion efficiency, excellent stress resistance, and stable fermentation performance to meet key demands in the brewing process",p18_3:" is of great significance for promoting the development of the traditional fermentation industry toward standardization and intelligentization.",p19:"<b>Topic 2: Discovery, Design, and Engineering of Novel Industrial Biocatalysts</b>",p19_1:'Background: Industrial enzymes are the core "chips" of biomanufacturing, widely used in food, feed, medicine, materials, energy, and other fields. Nevertheless, the vast majority of microorganisms in nature have not been cultivated, and their encoded enzyme resources—known as "enzymatic dark matter"—remain unexploited. Meanwhile, the deep integration of artificial intelligence and metagenomics is reshaping the paradigm of enzyme discovery, ',p19_2:"enabling efficient mining of special enzymes (such as proteases and amylases) with heat resistance, acid resistance, salt tolerance, organic solvent tolerance, and other properties from complex microbial communities. Developing novel industrial biocatalysts with independent intellectual property rights",p19_3:" is crucial for reducing bioprocess costs, replacing high-energy-consumption chemical catalysis, and realizing green and low-carbon manufacturing.",p20:"<b>Topic 3: Synergistic Biotransformation of Waste Biomass and CO₂ for Value-Added Products</b>",p20_1:"Background: Waste biomass (e.g., agricultural straw, forestry residues, food processing residues, etc.) and the greenhouse gas CO₂ are two abundant and widely available renewable carbon resources. Traditionally, they are treated separately—biomass is incinerated or landfilled, and CO₂ is directly emitted, resulting in low carbon utilization efficiency. Synthetic biology offers a new pathway for their synergistic conversion in the same biological system: biomass hydrolysate provides carbon skeletons and energy, while CO₂ serves as a supplementary carbon source, which is expected to significantly improve the carbon atom economy of target products. ",p20_2:'Developing synergistic conversion technology for "solid-gas dual carbon sources"',p20_3:" to support the green manufacturing of high-value products such as biofuels, biodegradable materials, and microbial proteins is a key direction of the circular economy under the dual carbon goals.",p21:"2.Wanhua Chemical Group Co., Ltd.",p22:'<b>Topic 1: Protein Production from Carbon Dioxide, Hydrogen and Synthetic Ammonia</b><br/> Background: At the beginning of Earth’s formation (about 4 billion years ago), the atmosphere was almost devoid of oxygen, filled with CO₂, N₂, H₂, CH₄ and H₂S. In such a "primordial soup", a group of organisms called chemolithoautotrophic archaea emerged. They do not rely on sunlight or consume organic matter, using only H₂ generated by geothermal-driven water-rock reactions as an energy source and CO₂ as the sole carbon source, forming the earliest life network on Earth near dark deep-sea hydrothermal vents. Reproducing the life wisdom of archaea synthesizing organic matter from CO₂ and H₂ 3.5 billion years ago, constructing an artificial carbon fixation system using synthetic biology to convert carbon dioxide, hydrogen and synthetic ammonia into single-cell protein. Ensuring the independent supply of feed protein and achieving a win-win situation for food security and carbon neutrality. ',p23:"<b>Topic 2: Cost Breakthrough in Cellulosic Sugar Production</b><br/> Background: Lignocellulosic biomass (straw, forestry waste, etc.) is the most abundant renewable carbon source on Earth. However, high pretreatment costs and low enzymatic hydrolysis efficiency lead to high cellulosic sugar costs, restricting the large-scale industrialization of bio-based materials. Considering the whole process of cellulosic sugar production, break through the production cost bottleneck through green pretreatment, efficient enzyme preparation development and process integration innovation, so that the production cost of cellulosic sugar ≤ 3,000 RMB/ton (competitive with starch sugar cost).",p24:"<b>Topic 3: Universal Biosensors for Key Metabolites</b><br/> Background: Current detection of intracellular key metabolites relies on metabolomics and other methods with long detection times, failing to obtain rapid results. Universal biosensors can be designed for rapid detection of key metabolites in glycolysis, PPP pathway, cofactors, TCA cycle, etc., to identify metabolic bottlenecks of strains.",p25:'<b>Topic 4: Construction of AI-Driven Fermentation Kinetics Prediction System and Fermentation Process Optimization</b><br/> Background: Biological fermentation processes are characterized by strong nonlinearity, time-variability and multivariable coupling. Offline detection of key biochemical indicators has a long lag, and traditional empirical process control suffers from low efficiency, poor batch stability and large fluctuations in product yield, restricting the large-scale upgrading of the fermentation industry. AI technology provides a new path for precise regulation of fermentation processes, but current kinetic prediction models have poor data fusion, high modeling thresholds, long modeling cycles and low adaptability between different processes. Considering the whole chain of AI model construction–kinetic feature mining–fermentation process optimization, integrate machine learning methods (e.g., Physics-Informed Neural Networks (PINN), Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM)) with fermentation kinetic equations, and integrate multi-source data (pH, dissolved oxygen, temperature, metabolite concentration, even metabolome, proteome, etc.) to build a high-precision hybrid "machine learning–fermentation kinetics" prediction model. Develop functional modules for real-time monitoring, trend prediction and process optimization, realizing early prediction of key fermentation indicators and ≥20% improvement of key indicators after process optimization, providing an intelligent guidance scheme for industrial fermentation production.',p26:"<b>Topic 5: Universal Biosensors for Heavy Metal Detection</b><br/> Background: Current heavy metal detection in wastewater cannot achieve rapid and accurate results. Biosensors enable trace and rapid detection of heavy metals including Hg²⁺, Pb²⁺, Cd²⁺, Zn²⁺, As³⁺, Au³⁺, Sb³⁺, UO₂²⁺, Ni²⁺, Cu²⁺.",p27:"<b>Topic 6: Microbial Treatment Technology for Chemical Waste Liquid (Alcohols, Aldehydes, Acids, Benzenes) to Greatly Reduce Wastewater Treatment Costs</b><br/> Background: Screen high-efficiency degrading strains for typical organic waste liquids (alcohols, aldehydes, acids, benzenes) in the chemical industry, construct a composite microbial treatment system to achieve targeted transformation and resource recovery of organic pollutants in waste liquids; or use high-concentration organic matter in wastewater as a carbon source, metabolically engineer strains to efficiently transform into high-value products such as single-cell protein, forming a low-cost, engineerable green treatment and resource utilization technical scheme.",p28:"3.Anhui Huaheng Biotechnology Co., Ltd.",p29:'<b>Topic 1: Discovery and Engineering Application of Key Enzymes from Marine Bacteria</b><br/> Background: Industrial enzymes serve as the core driving force for biomanufacturing, yet a vast amount of "enzymatic dark matter" in nature remains to be explored. Owing to their unique living environments (such as high salinity, high pressure, oligotrophy, etc.), marine bacteria have evolved enzyme resources with exceptional catalytic properties and tolerance to extreme conditions. Meanwhile, as synthetic biology expands to a broader range of chassis cells, the use of photosynthetic chassis or novel plant chassis for green carbon-fixation manufacturing has become a cutting-edge research direction. However, marine-derived enzymes often suffer from limited compatibility and expression efficiency in heterologous chassis. The deep integration of metagenomics and artificial intelligence enables efficient mining of key enzymes with industrial application potential (e.g., specific oxidoreductases, hydrolases, etc.) from novel chassis including marine bacteria. Rational design and directed evolution further enhance their catalytic performance and adaptability. This holds important strategic value for expanding the raw material spectrum of synthetic biology, reducing the cost of bioprocesses, and developing new biocatalysts.',p30:'<b>Topic 2: Synthetic Biomanufacturing and Pathway Reconstruction of High-Value Traditional Chinese Medicine Components</b><br/> Background: Traditional Chinese medicine (TCM) is a treasure of the Chinese nation. Its active ingredients, such as arbutin, terpenoids, flavonoids, etc., possess extremely high application value in medicine, healthcare, and daily chemical products (e.g., skin whitening and antioxidant effects). The production of traditional TCM ingredients mainly relies on plant extraction, which is confronted with bottlenecks including limited plant resources, long growth cycles, high vulnerability to climate changes, and high costs of extraction and purification, making it difficult to meet the growing market demand. Synthetic biology provides a disruptive approach for the green and sustainable production of high-value-added natural products. By elucidating the complex biosynthetic pathways of natural products in plants, and introducing key enzyme genes into easily cultivable microbial chassis (such as Escherichia coli and yeast), efficient "microbial cell factories" can be constructed to realize the customized and large-scale fermentative production of TCM ingredients. Focusing on high-value-added TCM ingredients, breaking through adaptive challenges such as heterologous reconstruction of complex metabolic pathways, balanced regulation of metabolic flux, and improvement of key enzyme activity, and developing high-yield and stable engineering strains are of great industrial significance for promoting the modernization of traditional Chinese medicine and green biomanufacturing.',p31:"<b>Topic 3: Creation and Application of Synthetic Biology Routes for Novel Green Pesticide Products</b><br/> Background: The sustainable development of agriculture has created an urgent demand for efficient, low-toxicity and environmentally friendly green pesticides. Traditional chemical pesticides are facing severe challenges such as increasing drug resistance, environmental residues and toxicity to non-target organisms. In contrast, biological pesticides (e.g., biostimulants, polypeptides, microbial metabolites, etc.) have become an important direction for the development of new pesticides due to their advantages including high target specificity and easy degradability. The introduction of synthetic biology technologies has made it possible to produce green pesticide active molecules with complex structures at low cost and on a large scale through microbial fermentation. Based on the actual needs of agricultural pest control and crop nutrition, designing and creating synthetic biological routes for novel green pesticides, and breaking through technical barriers such as poor chassis cell tolerance, incomplete synthetic pathways and difficulties in product separation and purification, are of great practical significance for accelerating the industrialization of green pesticides, serving modern agriculture and ensuring ecological security.",btn:"Register"}},form:{upload:"Upload",download:"Template",enter:"Enter",choose:"Choose",teamInfo:"Team Info",addMaterial:"Supplementary Materi",addMaterialSub:"Supplementary material required",teamName:"Team Name",enterTeamName:"Enter Your Team Name",conactEmail:"Contact (Team Leader)'s Email Address",enterConactEmail:"Enter Your Contact (Team Leader)'s Email Address",schoolName:"School Name",enterSchoolName:"Enter Your School Name",mailingAddress:"Deliver Address",enterMailingAddress:"Please Enter The Deliver Address to Accept The Starting Materials Required for The Competition",schoolIntro:"School Profile",competitionGrouping:"CompetitionGrouping",country:"Country",notice:"If You Cannot Find Data,Please Enter",itemInfo:"Project Info",itemName:"Project Name",enterItemName:"Enter Your Project Name",coupeArticle:"Popular Science Articles（ <span style='color:#c5c5ca'>Intended for explaining your whole project or a concept in your project to laymen, about 1000 words, and will compete for Best  Science Communication Award</span> ）.",emterCoupeArticle:"Word Document, Less Than 10Mb",itemLogo:"Project LOGO",enterItemLogo:"png/jpg/pdf Supported </br> Less Than 15Mb",itemIntro:"Project Brief Introduction and Schematic Diagram",enterItemIntro:"Please Enter a Project Profile of Less Than 2000 Words",itemVideo:"Project Video",enterItemVideo:"Less Than 300Mb",itemPoster:"Project Poster",enterItemPoster:"57x84cm (Lenth x Height)</br> png/jpg/pdf Supported </br> Less Than 15Mb",otherTitle:"Other Files (PDF Documents, No More Than 1Mb Each)",o1:"The School's Letter of Consent (Stamped) ",o2:"Integrity Declaration 